      "side": 1,
      "message": "Two manageResponders.spawn(...) sites in requester/spdm_responder_manager.cpp look unsafe — one in the processDiscoveredDevices loop body, one in notifyDeviceAdded. Both have the form:\n\n  manageResponders.spawn([this, device]() -\u003e sdbusplus::async::task\u003c\u003e {\n      co_await handleDeviceAdded(device);\n      co_return;                                                           \n  }());\n                         \nThe lambda is a temporary that\u0027s destroyed at the end of the full-expression — spawn(...) returns immediately after taking the coroutine handle. The coroutine frame\u0027s this then references the freed lambda, and the captured device is read at the first co_await against memory that\u0027s already been returned to the allocator. For a ResponderInfo (which holds a std::variant\u003cMctpResponderInfo, TcpResponderInfo\u003e with std::string inside), this can manifest as std::bad_variant_access: variant is valueless once the freed lambda storage gets reused.                                 \n                                                                                                                                             \nI hit this exact pattern when refactoring locally — wrote a small gtest fixture against SPDMResponderManager (one runtime-add of an MctpResponderInfo, then drain ctx) and got the valueless_by_exception trap reliably until I switched the spawn to                                                                         pass device as a coroutine parameter.   \n                                                                                                                                             \n89179 PS4\u0027s SPDMDiscovery::add already uses the safe form for the same reason — would suggest mirroring it here:\n\nmanageResponders.spawn(\n    [](SPDMResponderManager* self, ResponderInfo dev)\n        -\u003e sdbusplus::async::task\u003c\u003e {\n        co_await self-\u003ehandleDeviceAdded(std::move(dev));\n        co_return;\n    }(this, device));",
